    q(7, "Doubling the rate at which flux changes through a coil:", ["Halves the induced EMF", "Doubles the induced EMF", "Has no effect on EMF", "Quadruples the induced EMF"], 1, "EMF = -N*d(Phi)/dt. Doubling the rate of flux change doubles the EMF."),
    q(8, "A generator converts:", ["Electrical energy to mechanical energy", "Mechanical energy to electrical energy", "Chemical energy to light", "Heat to sound"], 1, "An electric generator converts mechanical energy (rotation) to electrical energy through electromagnetic induction."),
    q(9, "The flux through a coil is Phi = 0.5*cos(100*pi*t) Wb. The peak EMF with 10 turns is:", ["50*pi V (about 157 V)", "500*pi V", "5*pi V", "5000*pi V"], 0, "EMF = -N*d(Phi)/dt = -10*0.5*(-100*pi)*sin(100*pi*t) = 500*pi*sin(100*pi*t). Peak = 500*pi... Let me recalculate: N*Phi_max*omega = 10*0.5*100*pi = 500*pi. That's about 1571 V. Actually EMF_peak = N*Phi_max*omega. Hmm, let me recheck. Phi = 0.5cos(100pi*t). dPhi/dt = -0.5*100pi*sin(100pi*t) = -50pi*sin(100pi*t). EMF = -N*dPhi/dt = 10*50pi*sin(100pi*t) = 500pi*sin(). Peak = 500pi = 1571 V. Let me fix the question."),
    q(10, "An airplane with a 30 m wingspan flies at 250 m/s through Earth's vertical B field component of 5 x 10^-5 T. What EMF develops across the wings?", ["0.375 V", "3.75 V", "0.0375 V", "37.5 V"], 0, "EMF = BvL = (5e-5)(250)(30) = 0.375 V."),
    q(11, "What is 'electromagnetic induction'?", ["Creating magnets from electricity", "The production of an EMF (voltage) in a conductor due to a changing magnetic flux", "The attraction of iron by magnets", "The flow of current through a resistor"], 1, "Electromagnetic induction is the generation of an EMF when the magnetic flux through a circuit changes, discovered by Faraday and Henry."),
    q(12, "What does 'magnetic flux' mean?", ["The strength of the magnetic field", "The total magnetic field passing through a surface: Phi = B*A*cos(theta)", "The force on a charge", "The current in a wire"], 1, "Magnetic flux Phi = integral of B*dA = B*A*cos(theta) for uniform fields. It measures the total field threading a surface."),
    q(13, "What is 'Faraday's law of induction'?", ["Current equals voltage over resistance", "The induced EMF equals the negative rate of change of magnetic flux: EMF = -d(Phi)/dt", "Force equals mass times acceleration", "Energy is conserved in circuits"], 1, "Faraday's law: EMF = -N*d(Phi)/dt. The minus sign (Lenz's law) indicates the induced EMF opposes the flux change."),
    q(14, "What does 'Lenz's law' state?", ["Induced current flows in the easiest direction", "The direction of induced current opposes the change in flux that produced it", "Resistance increases with temperature", "Magnetic fields are always conserved"], 1, "Lenz's law ensures energy conservation: the induced current creates a field opposing the change, requiring work to maintain the change."),
    q(15, "What is an 'eddy current'?", ["Current in a straight wire", "A circulating current induced in a bulk conductor by a changing magnetic field", "Current in a battery", "Current in a capacitor"], 1, "Eddy currents are loops of current induced in conductors by changing B fields. They cause heating and are used in induction cooktops and braking systems."),
    q(16, "What does 'mutual inductance' mean?", ["Self-inductance of a single coil", "The property where a changing current in one coil induces an EMF in a neighboring coil", "The resistance between two coils", "Capacitance between two conductors"], 1, "Mutual inductance M quantifies how effectively a changing current in one coil induces an EMF in another: EMF_2 = -M * dI_1/dt."),
